Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.06,0:00:03.53,English,,0,0,0,,Have you ever noticed that a loudspeaker is the opposite of an eardrum?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.01,0:00:06.02,English,,0,0,0,,Eh, probably not, But it’s true!
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.27,0:00:09.58,English,,0,0,0,,See, our ears work by concentrating changes in air pressure onto
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.58,0:00:13.28,English,,0,0,0,,a small diaphragm that will move back and forth with the pressure changes.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.58,0:00:17.00,English,,0,0,0,,This vibration causes stimulation in the heary bits of the ear,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.00,0:00:20.29,English,,0,0,0,,which your brain can, assuming you have normal hearing ability,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.29,0:00:22.29,English,,0,0,0,,turn into what we perceive as sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.73,0:00:26.51,English,,0,0,0,,A loudspeaker does the opposite--its diaphragms (the driver cones)
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.51,0:00:28.70,English,,0,0,0,,vibrate to create pressure changes in the air.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.06,0:00:32.40,English,,0,0,0,,This vibration gets transferred to our eardrums, so we can hear it.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.67,0:00:35.80,English,,0,0,0,,We’re sticking to simple stuff today because the rabbit hole is just too deep.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.17,0:00:39.71,English,,0,0,0,,All you need to know is that things vibrate, which causes air pressure to fluctuate,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.71,0:00:43.15,English,,0,0,0,,which causes our eardrums to also vibrate, which stimulates the brain
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.15,0:00:46.08,English,,0,0,0,,so that we can perceive that vibration as sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.46,0:00:50.33,English,,0,0,0,,This channel started as a series exploring the history of artificial sound,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.33,0:00:54.00,English,,0,0,0,,and it’s been over TWO YEARS since I last touched on it at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.58,0:00:59.44,English,,0,0,0,,Finally we’re finishing this up with the introduction of DIGITAL SOUND.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.04,0:01:04.45,English,,0,0,0,,Since it’s been forever, let’s go over a brief history of sound recording technologies.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.80,0:01:08.21,English,,0,0,0,,The first device which could reproduce a sound recording was the phonograph.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.62,0:01:12.65,English,,0,0,0,,Thomas Edison’s invention consisted of an artificial eardrum, which would vibrate along
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.65,0:01:17.29,English,,0,0,0,,with changes in sound pressure, and with the aid of a collecting horn, the vibration is
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.29,0:01:20.62,English,,0,0,0,,transferred into this stylus, creating an up-and-down motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.10,0:01:23.34,English,,0,0,0,,This carves a groove into a wax cylinder,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.34,0:01:26.32,English,,0,0,0,,and the vibrating stylus creates an imprint of the sound wave.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.83,0:01:31.95,English,,0,0,0,,The depth of that groove becomes a literal analog of the original sound vibrations.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.14,0:01:35.24,English,,0,0,0,,Then, when the stylus is run over the now bumpy groove,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.24,0:01:39.09,English,,0,0,0,,the bumps cause the diaphragm to vibrate in the same way as it did
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.09,0:01:43.33,English,,0,0,0,,when it first made the bumps, and the result is that you hear the same sound as before.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.09,0:01:47.52,English,,0,0,0,,Or at least, a barely passable imitation of that sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.76,0:02:06.31,English,,0,0,0,,Commercially produced discs and cylinders were molded from master recordings,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.31,0:02:09.11,English,,0,0,0,,and wouldn’t wear down like the original wax cylinders.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.53,0:02:11.56,English,,0,0,0,,They were played back using devices like this,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.94,0:02:14.44,English,,0,0,0,,This device is called a reproducer, and for decades,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.44,0:02:18.02,English,,0,0,0,,all phonographs were based on simple acoustic devices like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.32,0:02:22.32,English,,0,0,0,,For nearly a century, this is how artificial sound recording technologies worked.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.73,0:02:25.40,English,,0,0,0,,Something (like this horn) would collect sound waves,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.40,0:02:28.04,English,,0,0,0,,and recreate them onto a physical analog.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.35,0:02:33.01,English,,0,0,0,,Then, that physical analog could recreate the original sound waves when played back,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.63,0:02:36.99,English,,0,0,0,,While it all started with simple acoustic devices like this phonograph,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.16,0:02:38.90,English,,0,0,0,,eventually improvements were made.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.29,0:02:43.04,English,,0,0,0,,The development of the electronic microphone was perhaps the most important.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.29,0:02:48.34,English,,0,0,0,,Now, sound waves cause a receiving diaphragm to move a coil of wire around a magnet,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.68,0:02:51.80,English,,0,0,0,,and a voltage is produced in the wire as the diaphragm moves.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.32,0:02:56.44,English,,0,0,0,,This time, sound waves are recreated as a voltage coming from the microphone,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.44,0:03:00.50,English,,0,0,0,,and by amplifying this voltage and sending it into a new record cutting device
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.50,0:03:04.01,English,,0,0,0,,which moves its cutting stylus as a function of the voltage it receives,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.36,0:03:08.34,English,,0,0,0,,a more accurate carving of the sound wave could be made into a disc or cylinder.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.90,0:03:11.82,English,,0,0,0,,This greatly improved the fidelity of the recorded sound,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.82,0:03:14.46,English,,0,0,0,,even on acoustic reproduction devices like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.76,0:03:17.65,English,,0,0,0,,With the proliferation of radio, which I feel I must explain
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.65,0:03:20.56,English,,0,0,0,,is a sound transmission technology, not sound recording,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.86,0:03:25.40,English,,0,0,0,,Just so we don’t get confused too much here, the loudspeaker became a big deal.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.78,0:03:30.01,English,,0,0,0,,Loudspeakers are the opposite of microphones. Instead of producing a voltage
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.01,0:03:34.34,English,,0,0,0,,as a reaction to a sound pressure wave moving its diaphragm, a loudspeaker will
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.34,0:03:38.57,English,,0,0,0,,move its diaphragm and create a pressure wave as a reaction to incoming voltage.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.14,0:03:43.70,English,,0,0,0,,With loudspeakers all the rage, record players could now use a phonograph cartridge,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.84,0:03:46.02,English,,0,0,0,,which acts like a microphone for records.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.41,0:03:50.34,English,,0,0,0,,The movement of the stylus as the groove vibrates it generates a voltage,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.34,0:03:53.16,English,,0,0,0,,which can be amplified to drive a loudspeaker.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.16,0:03:55.73,English,,0,0,0,,This gets very meta very quickly.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.09,0:03:58.34,English,,0,0,0,,An artificial ear turns sounds into voltage,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.34,0:04:01.70,English,,0,0,0,,and a cutting stylus turns this voltage into a groove on a record,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.99,0:04:07.84,English,,0,0,0,,Then, a playback stylus playing the record generates a voltage as the stylus vibrates,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.84,0:04:12.04,English,,0,0,0,,This voltage is then amplified to drive a loudspeaker, which causes pressure changes
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.04,0:04:16.39,English,,0,0,0,,in the air around the loudspeaker, which your ears concentrate down to your eardrums, and
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.39,0:04:21.07,English,,0,0,0,,now your real eardrums are vibrating in roughly the same way that the original artificial
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.07,0:04:24.33,English,,0,0,0,,eardrum moved in the microphone in the first place,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.33,0:04:25.33,English,,0,0,0,,Yeah,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.33,0:04:30.35,English,,0,0,0,,In essence, the record becomes a way to recreate the original pattern of voltage created by
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.35,0:04:36.26,English,,0,0,0,,the microphone, so that the sound can be heard again in a different place at a different time,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.26,0:04:38.88,English,,0,0,0,,Let’s cut out the middle bit because that’s what’s most confusing,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.88,0:04:42.43,English,,0,0,0,,A microphone like this creates an electrical signal of fluctuating intensity
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.43,0:04:44.69,English,,0,0,0,,based on how its diaphragm moves,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.69,0:04:47.92,English,,0,0,0,,I can just amplify that signal and send it straight into a loudspeaker,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.92,0:04:50.84,English,,0,0,0,,which will reproduce the sound in real time,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.84,0:04:54.40,English,,0,0,0,,Radio accomplishes this wirelessly, but the sound isn’t recorded,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.40,0:04:58.04,English,,0,0,0,,To capture the sound coming from the microphone to be played back later,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.04,0:05:01.77,English,,0,0,0,,it has to be converted into an analog of the signal,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.77,0:05:04.90,English,,0,0,0,,And that’s why it’s called analog recording technology,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.90,0:05:07.93,English,,0,0,0,,No matter if it’s a record, a cassette tape, an open reel tape,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.93,0:05:12.37,English,,0,0,0,,or even a wax cylinder, the sound information is recorded “doorectly”...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.37,0:05:14.37,English,,0,0,0,,Doorectly, Doorectly?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.37,0:05:17.38,English,,0,0,0,,The sound information is recorded directly onto something,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.38,0:05:22.11,English,,0,0,0,,which can then be used to recreate a copy of the original sound information,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.11,0:05:25.72,English,,0,0,0,,That something is an analog of the original sound waves,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.72,0:05:30.10,English,,0,0,0,,Improvements in sound technology were for many years simply incremental,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.11,0:05:32.53,English,,0,0,0,,Wax cylinders became shellac discs,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.53,0:05:34.11,English,,0,0,0,,Shellac became vinyl,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.11,0:05:38.10,English,,0,0,0,,Magnetic recording wire allowed for a reusable, electronic recording medium,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.10,0:05:42.60,English,,0,0,0,,This was improved into magnetic tape, allowing for a high fidelity, versatile recording medium
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.60,0:05:45.34,English,,0,0,0,,enabling multi-track recording and editing,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.34,0:05:49.40,English,,0,0,0,,And to improve on the noise of magnetic tape, different particle formulations were developed,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.40,0:05:51.54,English,,0,0,0,,and noise reduction technologies matured,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.54,0:05:54.36,English,,0,0,0,,But we were still just taking some signal from a microphone,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.36,0:05:59.04,English,,0,0,0,,then slapping it basically as is onto some sort of physical medium,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.04,0:06:01.42,English,,0,0,0,,And that medium was never perfect,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.42,0:06:04.49,English,,0,0,0,,Poorly made tape would cause signal dropouts,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.49,0:06:09.50,English,,0,0,0,,Discs would be plagued by dust and scratches, and would slowly wear down with each play,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.50,0:06:13.30,English,,0,0,0,,Because the analog medium contained the sound in its physical properties,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.30,0:06:16.77,English,,0,0,0,,it was inherently prone to wear, damage, and distortion,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.77,0:06:21.68,English,,0,0,0,,Which of course would wear down, damage, or distort the sound recording itself,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.68,0:06:24.43,English,,0,0,0,,If only there were some way to encode the sound,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.43,0:06:28.68,English,,0,0,0,,perhaps a way to store sound logically rather than analogously,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.68,0:06:32.91,English,,0,0,0,,Maybe if the signal weren’t the sound itself, but instead were a set of instructions on
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.91,0:06:37.60,English,,0,0,0,,how to recreate it, we could get lossless, near-perfect sound reproduction,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.60,0:06:40.01,English,,0,0,0,,And thus, digital sound was born,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.01,0:06:44.77,English,,0,0,0,,The heart of uncompressed digital sound is pulse-code modulation, or PCM,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.77,0:06:49.84,English,,0,0,0,,PCM’s roots can be traced back to the telegraph days, but its invention
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.84,0:06:53.51,English,,0,0,0,, as we know it today for sound came from British Engineer Alec Reeves,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.51,0:06:58.45,English,,0,0,0,,I feel I must compliment Mr, Reeves on his given name, it’s excellent, very good,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.45,0:07:01.90,English,,0,0,0,,He first devised this digital method of transmitting and receiving voice communication
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.90,0:07:06.89,English,,0,0,0,,in 1937, though it required extremely complex circuitry for the time,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.89,0:07:11.21,English,,0,0,0,,However, PCM transmission was used during World War 2 as a way to encrypt
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.21,0:07:17.62,English,,0,0,0,,extremely important voice conversations, such as those between PM-WC and POTUS-R.Jr.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.62,0:07:19.80,English,,0,0,0,,This encryption system was called SIGSALY,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.80,0:07:22.02,English,,0,0,0,,“SIGSALLY”? “SIGSALIE”?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.46,0:07:26.98,English,,0,0,0,,Or Project X, X System, Ciphony 1, or Green Hornet,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.99,0:07:30.84,English,,0,0,0,,Anyway, Project Green Sally X System Hornet 1 was much more complicated than
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.84,0:07:35.45,English,,0,0,0,,simple Pulse Code Modulation, but PCM was a large part of its encryption,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.45,0:07:37.37,English,,0,0,0,,So how does PCM work?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.37,0:07:39.63,English,,0,0,0,,It’s actually simpler than it might seem at first,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.63,0:07:43.98,English,,0,0,0,,It’s rather like a system for repeatedly asking what the instantaneous amplitude of
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.98,0:07:48.98,English,,0,0,0,,a signal is many thousands of times per second, then simply writing that down,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.98,0:07:51.20,English,,0,0,0,,Let’s look at a simple sine wave,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.20,0:07:55.11,English,,0,0,0,,If this were to be encoded on a vinyl record, the groove of the record would start out
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.11,0:07:58.76,English,,0,0,0,,straight in the center, then move to the left as the signal intensity reached peak,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.76,0:08:01.51,English,,0,0,0,,then it would start to move to the right, keep moving, keep moving, and then
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.51,0:08:03.67,English,,0,0,0,,it would pull back to the center,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.67,0:08:07.30,English,,0,0,0,,When it’s played back, the movement of the stylus as the walls of the groove
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.30,0:08:10.64,English,,0,0,0,,wiggle it back and forth will recreate this signal,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.64,0:08:14.80,English,,0,0,0,,And audio tape does the same thing, except the intensity isn’t recorded as a physical
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.80,0:08:18.08,English,,0,0,0,,movement, but as a degree of magnetization on the tape,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.08,0:08:21.65,English,,0,0,0,,But with PCM, we aren’t even trying to recreate the wave,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.65,0:08:24.98,English,,0,0,0,,Instead, we want to quantify it and play connect-the-dots,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.98,0:08:28.32,English,,0,0,0,,Let’s say I want to take 20 samples of this waveform,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.32,0:08:31.14,English,,0,0,0,,OK, I’ll divide it up into 20 chunks,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.14,0:08:34.82,English,,0,0,0,,Now I just need to define the detail I can have within each sample,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.82,0:08:37.04,English,,0,0,0,,Let’s put this on a scale of 0 to 15,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.04,0:08:38.94,English,,0,0,0,,That's 4 bits of resolution,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.94,0:08:42.89,English,,0,0,0,,Now, at each sampling point, we can take the closest value,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.89,0:08:46.92,English,,0,0,0,,This sine wave can now be represented as the following string of numbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.92,0:08:50.37,English,,0,0,0,,To get the sine wave back, we simply plot those numbers on a graph,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.37,0:08:52.52,English,,0,0,0,,Then, connect the dots,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.52,0:08:55.08,English,,0,0,0,,Tada! A sine… wave?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.50,0:08:56.98,English,,0,0,0,,Well, a sloppy sine wave,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.99,0:08:59.36,English,,0,0,0,,But that’s only because we weren’t very specific,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.36,0:09:03.77,English,,0,0,0,,We only took 20 samples, and each one could only be one of 16 values,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.77,0:09:06.68,English,,0,0,0,,But now we know the two most crucial parts of digital sound--
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.68,0:09:09.27,English,,0,0,0,,the sample rate and the bit depth,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.27,0:09:15.00,English,,0,0,0,,Perhaps the most common sample rate and bit depth of digital sound is 44.1 kHz, 16 bits,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.00,0:09:19.64,English,,0,0,0,,This means that every second, 44,100 samples are taken, and each sample can be
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.64,0:09:24.72,English,,0,0,0,,one of 65,536 values, or 2 to the power of 16,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.72,0:09:29.36,English,,0,0,0,,And that’s how devices like this, a Tascam DR-05, record sound,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.36,0:09:34.24,English,,0,0,0,,It’s looking at the voltage coming from the microphone, and taking precise measurements,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.24,0:09:40.61,English,,0,0,0,,Every 44,1 thousandth of a second, it takes a voltage reading, and, well, writes it down,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:40.61,0:09:45.87,English,,0,0,0,,It’s furiously quantifying and logging the voltage it measures with 16 bits of accuracy,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.87,0:09:49.55,English,,0,0,0,,and the result is a string of numbers that logically represent the shape of the
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.55,0:09:53.00,English,,0,0,0,,sound waves that exerted pressure on the microphone’s diagram,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:53.43,0:09:54.61,English,,0,0,0,,Pretty neat, huh?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.61,0:09:56.66,English,,0,0,0,,And it can actually write down two numbers at a time,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.66,0:10:00.18,English,,0,0,0,,since this has two microphones and records in stereo,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.18,0:10:04.78,English,,0,0,0,,Inside this recorder is what’s called an analog-to-digital converter, or ADC,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.78,0:10:09.45,English,,0,0,0,,The “ADC” is the actual device responsible for creating the stream of samples,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.45,0:10:12.39,English,,0,0,0,,It takes the analog signal coming from the microphones themselves
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.39,0:10:14.93,English,,0,0,0,,and converts it into a stream of discrete numbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.93,0:10:19.43,English,,0,0,0,,If you open the files it makes in audacity, you see what looks like a waveform of the sound,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.43,0:10:23.73,English,,0,0,0,,It is a waveform, but a waveform that’s been plotted precisely on a graph,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.73,0:10:25.87,English,,0,0,0,,Zoom way, way, way in on the waveform,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.87,0:10:29.31,English,,0,0,0,,and eventually you can see the individual samples themselves,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.31,0:10:31.22,English,,0,0,0,,And that’s all digital sound is--
Dialogue: 0,0:10:31.22,0:10:33.96,English,,0,0,0,,it’s a huge list of numbers strung together in order,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.96,0:10:36.90,English,,0,0,0,,To get these numbers back into sound we can hear, we need to use
Dialogue: 0,0:10:36.90,0:10:40.02,English,,0,0,0,,the opposite of an analog-to-digital converter, or “ADC”.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.02,0:10:43.47,English,,0,0,0,,So, we’ll use a DAC, or Digital-to-analog converter,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.47,0:10:46.13,English,,0,0,0,,I like it when names make sense,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.13,0:10:48.48,English,,0,0,0,,A DAC will read the string of numbers, and generate
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.48,0:10:51.32,English,,0,0,0,,an analog voltage based upon their values,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.32,0:10:55.15,English,,0,0,0,,The DAC will smooth out the choppiness of the samples a bit to make the resulting sound
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.15,0:10:59.97,English,,0,0,0,,a little more natural, and now you’ve got an analog signal to send into an amplifier
Dialogue: 0,0:10:59.97,0:11:01.92,English,,0,0,0,,and drive a loudspeaker,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.92,0:11:06.17,English,,0,0,0,,The result is a near-perfect reproduction of the originally recorded sound,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.17,0:11:11.02,English,,0,0,0,,Here’s a very crude analogy to explain the difference between analog and digital sound,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.02,0:11:16.00,English,,0,0,0,,A vinyl record’s walls generate an analog signal by moving the stylus left and right...
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.00,0:11:17.76,English,,0,0,0,,as well as up and down,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.76,0:11:19.79,English,,0,0,0,,It’s diagonally moved for stereo, but just
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.79,0:11:22.25,English,,0,0,0,,imagine for a moment that it’s just left and right,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.25,0:11:26.54,English,,0,0,0,,A record directly creates the analog signal via the motion of the stylus,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.54,0:11:32.21,English,,0,0,0,,But a digital sound source is instead sort of like a virtual stylus riding in a virtual groove,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.21,0:11:36.66,English,,0,0,0,,The sound samples are snapshots in time of where the stylus was,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.66,0:11:41.51,English,,0,0,0,,A DAC will then create an analog signal by running a virtual stylus through this
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.51,0:11:44.98,English,,0,0,0,,virtual groove and placing it at exactly the correct location--
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.98,0:11:49.83,English,,0,0,0,,and thus generating the appropriate voltage level--as defined by the samples,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.83,0:11:53.22,English,,0,0,0,,By using a giant list of numbers to recreate sound, instead of the
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.22,0:11:58.56,English,,0,0,0,,physical properties of a plastic disc, the sound can be reproduced flawlessly and accurately
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.56,0:12:02.83,English,,0,0,0,,with no reliance on the record player’s cartridge properties, the integrity of its stylus,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.83,0:12:05.80,English,,0,0,0,,it’s motor, the quality of the vinyl etc,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.80,0:12:10.22,English,,0,0,0,,The biggest boon of digital sound was that it eliminated all of the little nuances that
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.22,0:12:13.18,English,,0,0,0,,might change how a recording sounds,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.18,0:12:15.80,English,,0,0,0,,Digital sound is in a sense, absolute,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.80,0:12:20.73,English,,0,0,0,,But getting digital sound into the hands of the average consumer took a long while,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.73,0:12:25.44,English,,0,0,0,,DACs and “ADCs” were expensive components, and the amount of raw data generated by
Dialogue: 0,0:12:25.44,0:12:28.82,English,,0,0,0,,sound recording was immense for the standards of the time,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.82,0:12:32.82,English,,0,0,0,,Although 650 megabytes, the data equivalent of the first compact discs,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.82,0:12:38.87,English,,0,0,0,,is a paltry sum of data in the 21st century, it was unimaginably huge in the early 1970’s,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.87,0:12:42.37,English,,0,0,0,,when the first commercial digital sound recording took place,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.37,0:12:46.90,English,,0,0,0,,For context, the Commodore 64, released the same year as the compact disc,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.90,0:12:51.85,English,,0,0,0,,has 64 kilobytes of ram, and that was considered huge for the time,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:51.85,0:12:55.93,English,,0,0,0,,A compact disc held roughly ten thousands times as much data,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.93,0:13:00.08,English,,0,0,0,,64 kilobtyes of CD quality audio lasts this long;
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.36,0:13:00.75,English,,0,0,0,,About 0.4 sec.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.12,0:13:02.62,English,,0,0,0,,That’s not super helpful,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.62,0:13:05.95,English,,0,0,0,,When we continue, we’ll look at the methods that were used to store data from
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.95,0:13:10.08,English,,0,0,0,,digital recordings, and we’ll discuss the rise of the compact disc as a robust,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:10.08,0:13:14.02,English,,0,0,0,,consumer-friendly format for digital sound reproduction and distribution,
